A decomposition procedure based on locally-weighted regressions, known as STL decomposition [19], was used to decompose the time series into seasonal, trend-cycle and irregular components in order to assess the yearly seasonality of the number of confirmed malaria cases. The multiplicative model was used for all the time series. The mean absolute error (MAE) was in favour of a better fitting of the multiplicative model in comparison to the additive model for 86 of the 105 time series [20] (Additional file 1: Table S1). For the other 19 time series, the MAE difference between the two models was small. The multiplicative model is written as follows:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
